ntion": "LH", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 905, "end": 907}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3973"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "LHCGR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9872530698776245, "span": {"begin": 945, "end": 950}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "antral follicles", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.708893358707428, "span": {"begin": 955, "end": 971}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5351"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "LH", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1033, "end": 1035}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1081", "93659", "3342"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "human chorionic gonadotropin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9968823790550232, "span": {"begin": 1081, "end": 1109}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.828770101070404, "span": {"begin": 1081, "end": 1086}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:93659"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hCG", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9955018758773804, "span": {"begin": 1111, "end": 1114}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3973"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "LHCGR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.930435061454773, "span": {"begin": 1192, "end": 1197}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5351"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "LH", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1233, "end": 1235}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:93659"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hCG", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9920275807380676, "span": {"begin": 1248, "end": 1251}}, {"id": ["mesh:D007246"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fertility", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9993232488632202, "span": {"begin": 1304, "end": 1313}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "women", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.971772313117981, "span": {"begin": 1329, "end": 1334}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5351"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "LH", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1398, "end": 1400}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5351"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "LH", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1507, "end": 1509}}], "text": "Luteinizing hormone (LH) is a gonadotropin that is necessary for sexual maturation, ovulation, and therefore fertility. It is part of the glycoprotein hormone family and is organized as a heterodimer with a common &alpha;-subunit and a specific &beta;-subunit (Padmanabhan et al., 2018). An LH surge is needed and responsible for the downstream pathways that induce ovulation; this includes resumption of meiosis in the oocyte and cellular changes that allow rupture of the follicle to release the egg for fertilization. It increases intrafollicular proteolytic enzymes, weakening the wall of the ovary and allowing for passage of the mature follicle (Robker et al., 2018).  As follicles grow, estrogen synthesis increases in the female ovary. This in turn promotes GnRH pulses in the hypothalamus and increases the levels of luteinizing hormone (LH) released from the anterior pituitary. The circulating LH can then interact with its receptor (LHCGR) in antral follicles and stimulate ovulation (Duffy et al., 2019). In addition to LH, which is eliminated from the serum quickly, human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG), usually secreted during pregnancy, has a higher affinity with the receptor LHCGR and found longer in the serum than LH. Therefore, hCG is preferentially used for ovulation stimulation in fertility treatments for women and in animal studies (Russell and Robker, 2007).  Without the LH surge, the downstream pathways are not able to function and as a result, ovulation does not occur. If the LH surge is delayed, then ovulation may be delayed as well and fails to occur within the correct time window. This can have a negative impact on the reproductive health of females and perturb the estrous cycle.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:16:01 +0000 2026"}